1. Overall

Let’s see where the AirBnB listings are located in New York City.

map_NYC_st <- get_map("New York City", zoom=12, 
                  source="stamen",maptype="toner-lite")
g <- ggmap(map_NYC_st)
g + geom_point(aes(x=longitude,y=latitude), data=airbnb, size=0.3, alpha=0.3, color="red")

g + geom_density_2d(aes(x = longitude, y = latitude), data = airbnb, size = 0.4, bins = 12) +
  stat_density2d(aes(x=longitude,y=latitude,fill = ..level.., alpha = ..level..),
                 data=airbnb, geom = 'polygon', bins=12) +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "green", mid="yellow", high = "red") +
  scale_alpha(range = c(0.00, 0.5)) + 
  annotate("text",x=-73.993680, y=40.762754, label="Midtown",
           color="Dark Blue",fontface=2, size=3) + 
  annotate("text",x=-73.981639, y=40.726128, label="East Village",
           color="Dark Blue",fontface=2, size=3) + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")
## Warning: Removed 7861 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density2d).

## Warning: Removed 7861 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density2d).

We see that most of the AirBnB listings in NYC are located at Midtown and East Village in Manhattan.

2. Renting out appartment vs. permanent rentals

airbnb$price <- as.numeric(gsub('\\$|,', '', airbnb$price))
df <- airbnb[which(airbnb$availability_365 != 0), ]
m <- ggplot(df, aes(x = availability_365))
m + geom_histogram(aes(fill = ..count..))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

df$periodic = ifelse(df$availability_365 < 180, "periodic rentals", "permanent rentals")
aggregate(df$price, by = list(df$periodic), FUN = mean)
